    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="629"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d629">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 165.102/79b</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW2" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-26">
                        <hi rend="italic">September 26, 1914</hi>.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>265. Is potash to be used for agricultural and manufacturing purposes and other
                    articles mentioned in recent instructions for American use only in same category
                    with cyanide, dyestuffs, chemicals, and medicines? Have called conference for
                    September 30 looking toward sending American ship to Rotterdam. Have you
                    suggestions for conference?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
